   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1818_02_25_page02.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE"/>Edgeworth Town 1818
                  <date when="1818-02-25">Feb<hi rend="superscript">y</hi></date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                     My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MileX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Miles</persName>
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>I have received a note this day from<lb/>
            Mr Ward, which assures me of his entire<lb/>
            confidence in his chief <hi rend="underline">messengers honesty<lb/>
            &amp; accuracy</hi>. "I cannot doubt" says he "that<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CrewX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Crewe</persName> franked it upon his recollection<lb/>
            but the messenger cannot remember, whether<lb/>
            the packet was delivered to the man who<lb/>
            brought it, or went with the office letters".<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>As you will see by the note<lb/>
            from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CrewX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Crewe</persName> &amp; by the letters I enclosed<lb/>
            you from the Post office, it is notwithstanding<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WardX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Wards</persName> believe to the contrary, most<lb/>
            probable that the packet never was franked<lb/>
            by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CrewX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Crewe</persName> and was never put into the<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1818_02_25_page03.jpg"/>
            Post office. My only remaining chance<lb/>
            is to your having it to your own messenger or<lb/>
            to his own immaculate messenger -- <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>If as I believe that shawl cannot be <choice>
                  <orig>re<lb/>
            covered</orig>
                  <reg>recovered</reg>
               </choice> I must set the loss down to the <unclear/>
               <lb/>
            of my own childish impatience &amp; after<lb/>
            this severe guinea check resolve to be wiser<lb/>
            in future &amp; save the money on something<lb/>
            else. My <hi rend="underline">eagerness</hi> however, (I won't call<lb/>
            it impatience this time) to present a shawl<lb/>
            to my dear Aunt, is yet unabated, but I will<lb/>
            be wise and patient this time as to the means of getting it over - A friend<lb/>
            come over, in the course of the next month who<lb/>
            will bring it over &amp; in the course of the<lb/>
            next fortnight I will send you accurate<lb/>
            directions - If you are not tired of buying<lb/>
            Shawls &amp; are not afraid of again suffering<lb/>
            anxiety, I will begin the business over<lb/>
            again, thus, Buy me a Crimson or a<lb/>
            </p>
            <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1818_02_25_page04.jpg"/>
            <p>Morone Colour, the border narrow, the border<lb/>
            of the first white shawl you sent me, was<lb/>
            elegant, &amp; well put on, the border of the last<lb/>
            Green Shawl, was ill put on &amp; the corners<lb/>
            ill turned down, so that it betrayed it to be<lb/>
            an imitation - I think more of the <unclear/>
               <lb/>
            of the colour &amp; of the elegance of the border than<lb/>
            the size, the white shawl was quite large<lb/>
            enough. As to the price, I don't limit<lb/>
            you, for I can pinch it <add>out</add> of of anything else<lb/>
            as I wish to have the Shawl for my Aunt<lb/>
            handsome and elegant -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Do pray tell me something of the Man<lb/>
            who is going out to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#II">India</placeName> to improve the<lb/>
               <unclear/> there? I have the great pleasure<lb/>
            to tell you that my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName> has been consider<lb/>
            ably better for the last two or three days.<lb/>
            I hope this may find <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MileX2">M<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi> Miles</persName> as well<lb/>
            as we wish him to be. I hope you received<lb/>
            the draught for £6..10..0 - <lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
            I am dear<lb/>
            Madam <add>your</add> obliged and troublesome Servant<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
